NT|^B@2
^*Bhondo717:^*N There were 2 issues with the play.  First the heart suit.  In general, if you have Qxxxx opposite AJx, it is better to lead low towards the J.  The reason being, if you lead the Q, even if south has the K, you are playing 2 honors to knock out one of the opponents honors. Basically, there are only 2 ways you are going to not lose any heart tricks. The more common way is if kiri has Kx of hearts. The other is if I have exactly 109 doubleton.  In general, you will lose 3, but kiri having Kx is much more likely than me specifically having 109 exactly. |
PG| ***** 62 ***** |


NT|^B@2
^*Bhondo717:^*N Additionally, if kiri happens to have the stiff K, the way you played it you could lose 2 hearts. Whereas if you lead low, you only lose on heart.  So in general, when you have a choice if finessing, it is better to lead low than lead an honor. The other issue in the play of course is keeping track of the entries.  Once you are on the board with the Q of diamonds, you can take the club finesse at that point. If it works, you make. If it doesn't you are down 1. Here, it happens to work and the contract is makable.|
